Excellent catch — and this shows your understanding is becoming deep.

You noticed this line:

“Here the LLM gets access to the calculator tool and typically uses it ONCE…”

And you asked:

Why am I saying tool calling usually uses the tool only once?

Why can’t tool calling handle multiple tool calls just like agents?

This is THE RIGHT QUESTION, and the answer will make everything clear.

Let’s go step-by-step and end this confusion permanently.

⸻

🟦 1) ✔ TOOL CALLING CAN technically make multiple calls

Yes — you are right.

Tool calling is NOT LIMITED to one call.

Modern LLMs (GPT-4o, GPT-5, Claude 3, Gemini 1.5)

CAN:

	•	call a tool

	•	use that output

	•	call the tool AGAIN

	•	and again

	•	then return a final answer

So the limitation is NOT in the model.

The limitation is in how the chain is built.

Let’s break this down.

⸻

🟩 2) Why pure tool calling behaves like “one shot” in LangChain

When you write:

prompt | llm.bind_tools([...]) | parser

You are building a ONE-SHOT CHAIN:

Input → LLM → (maybe tool) → Output → END

Once the model outputs a tool call like:

{"tool": "calculator", "arguments": {…}}

LangChain does:

	•	run the tool

	•	return the tool result

	•	STOP THE CHAIN

There is no second pass of the model unless YOU manually feed it again.

🔥 So by default:

The pipeline ends after ONE tool call.

Even though the LLM wants to call more tools, the pipeline structure stops it.

This is by design — to keep pipelines predictable.

⸻

🟧 3) Agents solve this limitation

Agents in LangChain create a loop around tool calling:

THINK → TOOL → THINK → TOOL → THINK → FINAL ANSWER

Agents automatically:

	•	take tool result

	•	feed it back into model

	•	interpret the next thought

	•	run next tool

	•	repeat until final answer

This loop does NOT exist in simple tool calling.

That loop is the ONLY difference.

Tool calling has no loop → 1 call

Agent has loop → many calls

⸻

