🟦 Tool calling (default)

User

  ↓

LLM decides a tool call

  ↓

Tool runs

  ↓

Return result

  ⛔ STOP

🟩 Agent

User

  ↓

LLM: Thought #1

  ↓

Tool call #1

  ↓

LLM: Thought #2

  ↓

Tool call #2

  ↓

LLM: Thought #3

  ↓

...

  ↓

LLM: Final answer

Agents AUTOMATICALLY loop.

Tool-calling chains DO NOT.

Unless you manually create the loop (which is what LangGraph eventually does).

⸻

🟦 4) Why doesn’t basic tool calling auto-loop?

Because simple tool-calling chains were designed to be:

	•	predictable

	•	non-recursive

	•	safe

	•	single-step for API integration

	•	transparent

	•	cheap

If every simple chain auto-looped:

	•	infinite loops could occur

	•	unpredictable behavior

	•	costly multi-step runs

	•	developer loses control

	•	output becomes unstable

So LangChain intentionally made basic tool calling one-shot.

Agents were created to solve the “multi-step” requirement safely.

⸻

🟩 5) Does the LLM WANT to call multiple tools sometimes?

YES.

LLMs like GPT-4o can do multi-step tool reasoning.

But in basic tool-calling pipelines,

there is no mechanism to feed the tool result back to the model.

So the LLM does:

	•	first tool call

	•	returns

	•	chain ends

Agents introduce a reasoning loop.

⸻

🟦 6) A simple example that proves the difference

User:

First add 10 + 20, then multiply the result by 3.

Basic Tool Calling (no loop):

	•	LLM creates ONE tool call:

"add(10,20)"

	•	Tool returns 30

	•	Chain stops

	•	LLM never gets to “multiply by 3”

Agent:

	•	Thought: I should add 10+20 → tool call

	•	Result = 30

	•	Thought: Now multiply 30 × 3 → tool call

	•	Result = 90

	•	Final answer.

See the difference?

⸻

🟧 7) So in summary:

✔ Tool Calling (basic chain):

	•	LLM can call a tool

	•	Chain stops after the first tool execution

	•	No reasoning loop

	•	No multi-step planning

	•	Only continues if you manually chain multiple calls

✔ Agent:

	•	Adds a reasoning loop

	•	Automatically chains tool → thought → tool → thought

	•	Supports multi-step plans

	•	Supports error handling, retries, backtracking

	•	More powerful but less predictable

⸻

🟩 8) WHY LangChain separates them?

Because they solve different use cases:

✔ Tool calling:

	•	Simple tasks

	•	One-shot utility

	•	API integration

	•	No need for complex reasoning

✔ Agents:

	•	Complex tasks

	•	Multi-step workflows

	•	Tools depending on previous tools

	•	Real assistants

	•	Dynamic task solving

⸻

⭐ Final Crystal-Clear Answer to Your Question

🚨 If tool calling “only uses one tool”, it’s NOT because:

❌ the model can’t

❌ the tool can’t

❌ the LLM is weak

✔ It’s because:

basic tool-calling pipelines do NOT have a loop to continue reasoning.

✔ Agents ADD this loop.

✔ Workflows PROVIDE fixed sequence defined by YOU.

