⸻

1️⃣ What bind_tools([...]) actually does

When you do:

llm_with_tools = llm.bind_tools([add_tool, multiply_tool])

result = (prompt | llm_with_tools | parser).invoke(...)

You are saying:

“Dear LLM, in this one turn, you are allowed to choose from these tools

and output some tool calls (possibly more than one) in your response.”

So in that one pass, the model might output something like:

[

  {

    "name": "add_tool",

    "arguments": { "a": 10, "b": 20 }

  },

  {

    "name": "multiply_tool",

    "arguments": { "a": 30, "b": 3 }

  }

]

Two important things:

	1.	That’s still one LLM call (one “round”).

	2.	The 30 in the second call is based on the model’s own mental math, not the actual output from running add_tool.

So it’s thinking 10 + 20 = 30 in its brain, then calling multiply_tool(30, 3).

It is not:

	1.	Calling add_tool

	2.	Waiting for the real tool output 30

	3.	Then using that to build the second tool call

Because in a single call, it cannot see “real” tool outputs yet.

⸻

2️⃣ Why you still need a loop for true sequencing

Your scenario:

“First add 10 + 20, then multiply the result by 3.”

There are two different interpretations:

❌ Interpretation A (no loop, one model call)

“Figure out 10 + 20 in your head, then multiply by 3, and optionally call tools that match the final answer.”

Tools are not really needed here; the LLM can do all the math itself.

If it outputs two tool calls in one message, both are based on its own math, not on actual tool outputs.

This is not true tool chaining, it’s just one-shot thinking.

⸻

✅ Interpretation B (true tool-based multi-step)

We want:

	1.	Call tool 1 → add(10,20)

	2.	Get real output: 30 (from Python, DB, external system, etc.)

	3.	Use that real 30 to build next call: multiply(30, 3)

	4.	Then maybe another tool, etc.

To do THIS, you need:

LLM (decide tool) → tool → LLM (see result) → tool → LLM → ...

                 ↑                         ↑

              one round                next round

That “next round” is the loop I was talking about.

	•	Basic prompt | llm.bind_tools([...]) | parser

👉 gives you one round.

	•	An Agent (or your own loop) sits around this and does:

👉 call model → run tool → call model again → run tool again → etc.

⸻

3️⃣ So what does binding multiple tools actually change?

Binding multiple tools like:

llm_with_tools = llm.bind_tools([add_tool, multiply_tool])

means:

	•	In that single LLM turn, it has a choice of tools.

	•	It might pick:

	•	only add_tool, or

	•	only multiply_tool, or

	•	both (but using its own reasoning for arguments, not real tool results).

Still one call, no loop, no sequential tool-chaining based on real outputs.

It’s like saying:

“You have a calculator and a currency converter on your desk.

In this one shot, write down which ones you’ll use and with what values.”

But you don’t actually run calculator, look at the screen, and then decide about the converter in a separate moment.

